  "prompt": "When is 70% isopropyl rubbing alcohol better than 91%?",
  "response": "70% isopropyl rubbing alcohol can be better than 91% in certain situations due to its lower concentration and slower evaporation rate. Here are a few scenarios where 70% might be preferred:\n\n1. **Disinfection and Sterilization**: \n   - 70% isopropyl alcohol is often more effective at killing bacteria and viruses than 91% because it remains on the surface longer, allowing more time to penetrate the cell walls of microorganisms. The higher concentration of 91% alcohol evaporates more quickly, which can reduce its effectiveness in killing certain germs.\n\n2. **Skin Application**:\n   - 70% alcohol is less drying and irritating to the skin compared to 91%. This makes it a better choice for use on the skin, especially for prolonged periods or on sensitive areas.\n\n3. **Surface Cleaning**:\n   - For some surfaces, 70% alcohol can be more effective because it remains wet longer, giving it more time to dissolve dirt and oils. The quicker evaporation of 91% alcohol might leave less time for thorough cleaning.\n\n4. **Electronic Devices**:\n   - While both concentrations can be used on electronics, 70% is generally safer because it is less likely to damage plastics and other materials due to its lower concentration and slower evaporation.\n\nIn summary, while 91% isopropyl alcohol is more potent and evaporates faster, 70% can be more effective for certain applications, particularly where longer contact time and less irritation are beneficial.",
